SKILL|test-driven-development|"TDD: enforce RED-GREEN-REFACTOR, tests before code."
STEP|1|Core principle:** If you didn't watch the test fail, you don't know if it tests the right thing.
STEP|2|Violating the letter of the rules is violating the spirit of the rules.**
STEP|3|Always:**
STEP|4|New features
STEP|5|Bug fixes
STEP|6|Refactoring
STEP|7|Behavior changes
STEP|8|Exceptions (ask the user first):**
STEP|9|Throwaway prototypes
STEP|10|Generated code
STEP|11|Configuration files
STEP|12|No exceptions:**
STEP|13|Don't keep it as "reference"
STEP|14|Don't "adapt" it while writing tests
STEP|15|Don't look at it
STEP|16|Delete means delete
STEP|17|Good test:**
STEP|18|Bad test:**
STEP|19|Requirements:**
STEP|20|One behavior per test
STEP|21|Clear descriptive name ("and" in name? Split it)
STEP|22|Real code, not mocks (unless truly unavoidable)
STEP|23|Name describes behavior, not implementation
STEP|24|MANDATORY. Never skip.**
STEP|25|Test fails (not errors from typos)
STEP|26|Failure message is expected
STEP|27|Fails because the feature is missing
STEP|28|Test passes immediately?** You're testing existing behavior. Fix the test.
STEP|29|Test errors?** Fix the error, re-run until it fails correctly.
STEP|30|Good:**
STEP|31|Bad:**
STEP|32|Cheating is OK in GREEN:**
STEP|33|Hardcode return values
STEP|34|Copy-paste
STEP|35|Duplicate code
STEP|36|Skip edge cases
STEP|37|MANDATORY.**
STEP|38|Test passes
STEP|39|Other tests still pass
STEP|40|Output pristine (no errors, warnings)
STEP|41|Test fails?** Fix the code, not the test.
STEP|42|Other tests fail?** Fix regressions now.
STEP|43|Remove duplication
STEP|44|Improve names
STEP|45|Extract helpers
STEP|46|Simplify expressions
STEP|47|If tests fail during refactor:** Undo immediately. Take smaller steps.
STEP|48|"I'll write tests after to verify it works"**
STEP|49|Might test the wrong thing
STEP|50|Might test implementation, not behavior
STEP|51|Might miss edge cases you forgot
STEP|52|You never saw it catch the bug
STEP|53|"I already manually tested all the edge cases"**
STEP|54|No record of what you tested
STEP|55|Can't re-run when code changes
STEP|56|Easy to forget cases under pressure
STEP|57|"It worked when I tried it" ≠ comprehensive
STEP|58|"Deleting X hours of work is wasteful"**
STEP|59|Delete and rewrite with TDD (high confidence)
STEP|60|Keep it and add tests after (low confidence, likely bugs)
STEP|61|"TDD is dogmatic, being pragmatic means adapting"**
STEP|62|Finds bugs before commit (faster than debugging after)
STEP|63|Prevents regressions (tests catch breaks immediately)
STEP|64|Documents behavior (tests show how to use code)
STEP|65|Enables refactoring (change freely, tests catch breaks)
STEP|66|"Tests after achieve the same goals — it's spirit not ritual"**
STEP|67|Code before test
STEP|68|Test after implementation
STEP|69|Test passes immediately on first run
STEP|70|Can't explain why test failed
STEP|71|Tests added "later"
STEP|72|Rationalizing "just this once"
STEP|73|"I already manually tested it"
STEP|74|"Tests after achieve the same purpose"
STEP|75|"Keep as reference" or "adapt existing code"
STEP|76|"Already spent X hours, deleting is wasteful"
STEP|77|"TDD is dogmatic, I'm being pragmatic"
STEP|78|"This is different because..."
STEP|79|All of these mean: Delete code. Start over with TDD.**
STEP|80|[ ] Every new function/method has a test
STEP|81|[ ] Watched each test fail before implementing
STEP|82|[ ] Each test failed for expected reason (feature missing, not typo)
STEP|83|[ ] Wrote minimal code to pass each test
STEP|84|[ ] All tests pass
STEP|85|[ ] Output pristine (no errors, warnings)
STEP|86|[ ] Tests use real code (mocks only if unavoidable)
STEP|87|[ ] Edge cases and errors covered
STEP|88|**Testing mock behavior instead of real behavior** — mocks should verify interactions, not replace the system under test
STEP|89|**Testing implementation details** — test behavior/results, not internal method calls
STEP|90|**Happy path only** — always test edge cases, errors, and boundaries
STEP|91|**Brittle tests** — tests should verify behavior, not structure; refactoring shouldn't break them
